## TLDR
* CloudFront uses [edge locations](https://aws.amazon.com/cloudfront/features/#Edge_Locations) globally to store content closer to users, ensuring faster delivery and reduced latency.
* It checks the cache before querying the origin server. This ensures faster responses for repeated requests.
* A [**Cache Key**](#cache-key) determines what constitutes the same request, helping CloudFront decide whether to serve cached content or fetch fresh data.
* [Headers](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers), cookies, and query strings can customize the Cache Key.
* **Cache Policy** defines caching behavior.
* **Origin Request Policy** specifies data sent to the origin server.
* The objective is to optimize cache hits and reduce origin requests.


## Introduction

When you visit a website, you expect it to load quickly. Howevever services like **[Amazon CloudFront](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2026-03-06-aws-123-Amazon-CloudFront/)** help make that happen by using [*caching*](https://aws.amazon.com/caching/).

### What is caching?

In computing, a cache is a high-speed data storage layer that stores a subset of data, typically transient, to serve future requests for that data faster than accessing the data’s primary storage location. Caching enables efficient reuse of previously retrieved or computed data.

[CloudFront](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2026-03-06-aws-123-Amazon-CloudFront/) stores copies of files (like images, videos, or web pages) in many locations around the world, called [**edge locations**](https://aws.amazon.com/cloudfront/features/#Edge_Locations). These are servers closer to users.

![image of caching in action](/blog/src/images/125/125-1.png)

### How does CloudFront caching work?

1. A user makes a request (for example, opening a webpage).
2. The nearest[ CloudFront edge location](https://aws.amazon.com/cloudfront/features/#Edge_Locations) checks:

   * Do I already have this file?
   * If yes, has it expired?
3. If the file is available and still valid . it’s sent back immediately (**cache hit**).
4. If not . the request is sent to the original server (called the *origin*).
5. The origin responds with the file.
6. CloudFront stores (caches) that file for future users.

**Serve as many requests as possible from the cache instead of the [origin](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/Introduction.html#origin).**

The origin is the source server where your content resides. It could be an Amazon S3 bucket, an HTTP server, or an AWS service like MediaPackage. CloudFront retrieves content from the origin when it is not available in the cache or when the cached content has expired. By reducing the number of requests sent to the origin, you can improve performance, reduce latency, and lower costs.

<h3 id="cache key">What is a Cache Key?</h3>

Every cached item needs a unique label so [CloudFront](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2026-03-06-aws-123-Amazon-CloudFront/) knows what’s what. This label is called a **Cache Key**.

A Cache Key is made up of:

* The **hostname** (e.g. `magicishaq.com`)
* The **path of the file** (e.g. `/about/us`)

If two users request the same URL, they’ll get the cached version.


Sometimes, the same page changes depending on:

* Language
* Device (mobile vs desktop)
* User preferences

In these cases, CloudFront needs more information to decide what to cache.

So, you can expand the Cache Key to include:

* **HTTP headers** (e.g. language)
* **Cookies** (user sessions)
* **Query strings** (extra info in the URL like `?size=large`)

This is controlled using a **cache policy**.



### Cache Policy

A cache policy tells [CloudFront](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2026-03-06-aws-123-Amazon-CloudFront/):

* What to include in the Cache Key
* How long to store content (called **TTL – [Time to Live](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2024-05-17-aws-63-Route53-TTL/)**)

You can choose:

* No headers/cookies/query strings (best performance)
* Only specific ones ([whitelist](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitelist_(computing)))
* All of them (most flexible, but slower caching)

But remember...

* More data the Cache Key has  = more accurate content
* fewer cache hits (worse performance)



### What is TTL ([Time to Live](https://magicishaqblog.netlify.app/2024-05-17-aws-63-Route53-TTL/))?

TTL defines how long something stays in the cache.

* Short TTL = fresh data, but more origin requests
* Long TTL = faster performance, but risk of outdated content

You can also manually remove cached content using something called [**invalidation**](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/Invalidation.html).



### Cache Policy vs Origin Request Policy

#### Cache Policy

* Decides **what affects caching**
* Determines the **Cache Key**

#### Origin Request Policy

* Decides **what gets sent to the origin server**
* Does **NOT affect caching**

**Cache Policy** determines what affects caching and the Cache Key, while **Origin Request Policy** decides what data is sent to the origin server without impacting caching.  

### A simple example

When caching, you can base the Cache Key on the URL and the language header, while ensuring that additional data like the user session ID and device type is sent only to the origin server. This approach allows CloudFront to maintain efficient caching performance by using the language header in the Cache Key, while still providing the origin server with the necessary session and device information to handle requests appropriately.

![image of example](/blog/src/images/125/125-2.png)


### Conclusion

Effective caching with Amazon CloudFront is essential for optimizing website performance, reducing costs, and enhancing user experience. By understanding and implementing caching strategies such as Cache Keys, Cache Policies, and TTL, you can ensure faster content delivery and minimize the load on your origin servers. Leveraging these tools allows you to build websites that are not only faster but also more reliable and scalable, meeting the demands of modern users.

